p <- ggplot(data = gss_sm, mapping = aes(x = bigregion, fill = religion))

A bit easier to compare heights, but for the middle areas still tough- when you can get away from it, side-by-side is best for comparing heights of subgroups (always with tradeoffs). Use position="dodge", with mapping = ..prop..:

p <- ggplot(data = gss_sm, mapping = aes(x = bigregion, fill = religion))
p + geom_bar(position = "dodge", 
             mapping = aes(y = ..prop.., group = religion))

or we can separate regions with facetting, and then maybe colors arent so important:

p <- ggplot(data =gss_sm, mapping = aes(x = religion))
p + geom_bar(position = "dodge", mapping = aes(y=..prop..,group = bigregion)) + facet_wrap(~bigregion, ncol = 2)

Histograms are straightforward: bins of (usually) uniform width are calculated over a single continuous variable and displayed as discrete bars. A bar chart is the same idea but bars are (usually) drawn for categories. ggplot is doing some calulcations under the hood in order to produce this: i.e.its another example of an indirect path from data to a plot, where intermediate calculations are hidden from view. But its a common use case, so good to have.

p <- ggplot(data = midwest, mapping = aes(x = area))
p + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# or an approx number of bins
p + geom_histogram(bins = 10)

# or a specific width
p + geom_histogram(binwidth = .001)

Comparisons (here stacked, not overlapped!). This split is acheived simply by mapping state to fill color. Removing that line would draw just a single filled area. Notice how subsetting is done in-situ, instead of assigning the subset to an indermediate object. That is a more verbose call, but keeps the workspace tidier.

oh_wi <- c("OH","WI")
p <- ggplot(data = subset(midwest, state %in% oh_wi),
            mapping = aes(x = percollege, fill = state))
p + geom_histogram(alpha = 0.4, bins = 20)

Or a kernel (smoothed) density of a continuous variable- same idea as a histogram, but it makes sense (IMO) when the data are large and actually have a semi-smooth pattern.

p <- ggplot(data = midwest, mapping = aes(x = area))
p + geom_density()

And again, by groups, and with semitransparent fills:

p <- ggplot(data = midwest,
            mapping = aes(x = area, fill = state, color = state))
p + geom_density(alpha = .3)

p <- ggplot(data = subset(midwest, state%in% oh_wi),
            mapping = aes(x = area, fill = state, color = state))
p + geom_density(alpha = .3, mapping = aes(y=..scaled..))

Chapter 5

In the previous chapter several ggplot shorthands were done, all of which imply some intermediate calculations from view. They are instead implied by using specific geoms that take care of some calculations for you. A potential problem might be that its not clear to the reader how the calculations were done. For example, with the GSS data we made dodged bar charts by religion and region, and it might not be obvious whether region or religion is supposed to sum to one. This sort of thing is why its often good to externalize all such data prep and make it explicit and legible to the reader of your code (usually yourself a week or more after having written it!!). This we do using several utility functions (whose names are verbs) in the tidyverse. Series of operations end up reading like a sentence. Heres an example:

To make rel_by_religion first take the gss_sm dataset, feed it to group_by() which sets data groupings (subsets) by bigregion and by religion within region, then feeds that output to summarize, where we make a new variable N, the count of individuals in each subset (nrow() in base R), then pass this modified object to mutate to calculate two new columns freq and pct (which is based on freq, created in the same call!!). Since thats an explicit call, we know that pct is the percent breakdown over religion within big regions. All this calculation was happening implicitly in previous calls to geom_bar().

rel_by_region <- gss_sm %>%
    group_by(bigregion, religion) %>%
    summarize(N = n()) %>%
    mutate(freq = N / sum(N),
           pct = round((freq * 100), 0))
## Warning: Factor `religion` contains implicit NA, consider using
## `forcats::fct_explicit_na`
p <- ggplot(data = rel_by_region, aes(x = bigregion, y = pct, fill = religion))
p + geom_col(position = "dodge") 

p <- ggplot(rel_by_region, aes(x = religion, y = pct, fill = religion))
p + geom_col(position = "dodge2") +
    coord_flip() + 
    facet_grid(~bigregion)

In the above trend panel plot, each individual trend is easy to identify and pick out, but theyre not necessarily easy to compare. The next one throws out the trend and instead summarizes overall variation in donor rates in each country, sorting countries (good practice better than alphabetical always!) by median donor levels, and coloring the boxes by some standard categories of worldviews that dominate each country. Thats weird to me because Im not a sociologist, but whatever.

# throw out trends and keep variation:
p <- ggplot(data = organdata, 
            mapping = aes(x = reorder(country, donors, FUN = median, na.rm = TRUE), y = donors, fill = world))
p + geom_boxplot()+ coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 34 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Another example of dplyr table pipeline, which reads "take the organdata dataset, then group it by the consent law variable, and by country within that, then take EACH numeric column (picked out using is.numeric) and get its mean and standard deviation within each of these subsets. na.rm tells us to ignore missing values. ungroup returns the dataset with these new variables to us with the group attribute removed (it might have unintended side effects if we left he group attribute on the new object).

by_country <- organdata %>% 
    group_by(consent_law, country) %>%
    # nice trick
    summarize_if(is.numeric, list(mean = mean, sd=sd), na.rm = TRUE) %>%
    ungroup()

Then we take this new data object that was created in an explicit way and make a dot plot (awesome and underused), where countries are stacked ordered on the newly created variable donor_mean.

p <- ggplot(data = by_country,
            mapping = aes(
                x = donors_mean, 
                y = reorder(country, donors_mean),
                          color = consent_law))
p + geom_point(size = 3) 

p <- ggplot(data = organdata,
            mapping = aes(x = reorder(country, donors, na.rm =TRUE),
                          y = donors, color = world))
p + geom_jitter(position = position_jitter(width = .15)) + coord_flip() 
## Warning: Removed 34 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
